qualcommbe: v6.12: update PCS patches to use .pcs_validate()

The original PCS driver did not use the .pcs_validate() in
phylink_pcs_ops. The patches for 1000/2500base-x and 10g modes were
taken from this old driver, and thus did not bother with
.pcs_validate(). Thus, even though these modes are supported, phylink
would not enable them.

ipq_pcs_clk_rate_get(). While the latter does not appear to change
behavior, it does change the clock rates listed under
/sys/kernel/debug/clk

realtek: overwrite c22 polling unconditionally on RTL930x

During setup the mdio driver decides the polling mode of the 4 smi
busses depending on the DTS phy settings. This works as follows:

- set polling to c45 if at least one phy is ethernet-phy-ieee802.3-c45
- set polling to c22 if all phys are ethernet-phy-ieee802.3-c22

On RTL930x it is not possible to switch to c22 if uboot has set c45
before. Fix this by overwriting the bitfield properly. While we are
here:

- Sort variables according to kernel style (inverse christmas tree)
- Initialize fields properly with  = { 0 }
- Use GENMASK() for better readability
- Make use of RTMDIO_MAX_SMI_BUS

uboot-envtools: set nonshared flag correctly per-subpackage

Currently, uboot-envtools is being built for a (shared) instruction
set (phase2 in buildbots) instead of target-specific (phase1 in builbots).
So the package does not contain the uci-defaults file specific for each
target_subtarget. (Only the fortunate target with coincidentally the same
instruction set and target as the SDK chosen by the buildbot will have the
uci-defaults file.)

This commit sets the nonshared flag correctly in the Makefile so that
uboot-envtools is built for the target-specific (phase 1).

This is done by using the PKGFLAGS variable which is intended for
per-binary flags (instead of PKG_FLAGS which has a global scope), as
stated in some old commits 349e7b635e[1], 2d7eaf2e15[2], 064e7c8f00[3] and
2cb75cd8b9[4].

While at here, use PKG_URL, instead of URL, which is intended for global
scope. As stated in commit e32edf712b[5].

scripts: getver.sh: approximate version from date

When doing package support and management it is often the case that
knowing the corresponding openwrt repo's release version is useful.

For example, when adding package changes to the ASU server, the
openwrt revision is used as the cutoff for applying those changes.
Knowing a package change's hash in its remote feed repo allows us
to look up its change date, which we can now use with getver.sh
to approximate the revision in openwrt at which it was made.

issue.body:
if you installed with atuomatic mode and wondering how to run multiple psiphon with different configs this is the way :)
```
sudo /etc/psiphon/psiphon-tunnel-core-x86_64 -config fr.config
sudo /etc/psiphon/psiphon-tunnel-core-x86_64 -config de.config
and so on

```

comment.body:
#!/bin/bash

# Exit on error and show commands
set -e
set -x

# Check if running as root
if [ "$EUID" -ne 0 ]; then
    echo "Please run as root using sudo"
    exit 1
fi

# Update system and install prerequisites
apt-get update
apt-get install -y wget jq iptables

# Create necessary directories
mkdir -p /etc/psiphon/instance{0,A,B,C,D,E}
mkdir -p /usr/share/psiphon/
mkdir -p /var/log/psiphon/

# Download necessary files
echo "Starting downloads"
wget -O /usr/share/psiphon/psiphon-tunnel-core-x86_64 \
    https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Psiphon-Labs/psiphon-tunnel-core-binaries/master/linux/psiphon-tunnel-core-x86_64
wget -O /tmp/psiphon.config.base \
    https://raw.githubusercontent.com/SpherionOS/PsiphonLinux/main/psiphon.config
echo "Core files downloaded"

# Function to create config files with guaranteed 0.0.0.0 binding
create_config() {
    local instance=$1
    local http_port=$2
    local socks_port=$3
    
    cp /tmp/psiphon.config.base /etc/psiphon/$instance/psiphon.config
    
    # Use jq for reliable JSON manipulation
    jq --argjson http_port "$http_port" \
       --argjson socks_port "$socks_port" \
       '.LocalHttpProxyPort = $http_port | 
        .LocalSocksProxyPort = $socks_port | 
        .BindInterface = "0.0.0.0" | 
        .AllowNoAuthorization = true' \
        /etc/psiphon/$instance/psiphon.config > /tmp/temp_config.json
        
    mv /tmp/temp_config.json /etc/psiphon/$instance/psiphon.config
}

# Create configs for all instances
create_config "instance0" 8080 1080
create_config "instanceA" 3169 4169
create_config "instanceB" 5169 6169
create_config "instanceC" 7169 8169
create_config "instanceD" 9169 10169
create_config "instanceE" 11169 12169

# Create launcher scripts
for instance in instance0 instanceA instanceB instanceC instanceD instanceE; do
    # For instance0, the command is just 'psiphon'
    if [ "$instance" = "instance0" ]; then
        command_name="psiphon"
    else
        # Remove the word 'instance' to get A, B, etc.
        suffix="${instance#instance}"
        command_name="psiphon$suffix"
    fi
    
    cat > /usr/bin/$command_name <<EOF
#!/bin/bash
cd /etc/psiphon/$instance
exec /usr/share/psiphon/psiphon-tunnel-core-x86_64 -config psiphon.config
EOF
    chmod +x /usr/bin/$command_name
done

# Make core binary executable
chmod +x /usr/share/psiphon/psiphon-tunnel-core-x86_64

# Configure firewall
ports=(8080 1080 3169 4169 5169 6169 7169 8169 9169 10169 11169 12169)
for port in "${ports[@]}"; do
    iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport $port -j ACCEPT
    echo "Allowed ALL to port $port"
done

# Save firewall rules
mkdir -p /etc/iptables
iptables-save > /etc/iptables/rules.v4

# Create supervisor script
cat > /usr/local/bin/psiphon-supervisor <<'EOF'
#!/bin/bash
trap 'kill $(jobs -p); exit 0' SIGTERM SIGINT

for instance in instance0 instanceA instanceB instanceC instanceD instanceE; do
    cd "/etc/psiphon/$instance"
    /usr/share/psiphon/psiphon-tunnel-core-x86_64 -config psiphon.config &
done

# Wait indefinitely
while true; do
    sleep 3600 &
    wait $!
done
EOF
chmod +x /usr/local/bin/psiphon-supervisor

# Create systemd service
cat > /etc/systemd/system/psiphon-multi.service <<'EOF'
[Unit]
Description=Psiphon Multi-Instance VPN Service
After=network.target

[Service]
Type=simple
ExecStart=/usr/local/bin/psiphon-supervisor
Restart=always
RestartSec=5s
StandardOutput=syslog
StandardError=syslog
SyslogIdentifier=psiphon-multi

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target
EOF

# Create uninstaller
cat > pluninstaller_multi <<'EOF'
#!/bin/bash
# Stop and disable service
systemctl stop psiphon-multi
systemctl disable psiphon-multi

# Remove files
rm -rf /etc/psiphon
rm -f /usr/bin/psiphon
rm -f /usr/bin/psiphon{A,B,C,D,E}
rm -rf /usr/share/psiphon
rm -f /usr/local/bin/psiphon-supervisor
rm -f /etc/systemd/system/psiphon-multi.service

# Reset firewall rules
ports=(8080 1080 3169 4169 5169 6169 7169 8169 9169 10169 11169 12169)
for port in "${ports[@]}"; do
    iptables -D INPUT -p tcp --dport $port -j ACCEPT 2>/dev/null
done

# Save firewall rules
iptables-save > /etc/iptables/rules.v4

echo "Psiphon multi-instance uninstalled"
EOF
chmod +x pluninstaller_multi

# Enable and start service
systemctl daemon-reload
systemctl enable --now psiphon-multi

# Final verification
echo "Waiting for instances to start (30 seconds)..."
sleep 30

echo ""
echo "Verifying port bindings:"
echo "=============================================================="
for port in "${ports[@]}"; do
    if ss -tulpn | grep ":$port" | grep -q "0.0.0.0"; then
        echo "Port $port: SUCCESS (listening on 0.0.0.0)"
    else
        echo "Port $port: FAILED (not listening correctly)"
    fi
done
echo "=============================================================="

echo ""
echo "Installation completed! All instances should be accessible from your LAN."
echo "Use 'systemctl status psiphon-multi' to check service status"
echo "Uninstall with: sudo ./pluninstaller_multi"
